Warning: Read This Before Buying an HP Laptop

If you want to waste your time and energy, and jeopardize your important work, you might want to consider HP.

I bought a high-end Ryzen 7 gaming laptop with a Care Pack. My standard warranty recently expired, but my laptop is still under Care Pack coverage. No one is listening, and it’s clear there is a problem with the HP battery. They are only making excuses.

firstComment:
Prezados @cdmaxoficial ,

Gostaria de registrar uma reclamação referente à compra de uma impressora HP realizada na loja CD Max, localizada no Pátio Água Fria. Ao utilizar o produto, percebi que o cartucho colorido estava seco, impossibilitando o uso adequado da impressora. Retornei à loja no dia seguinte, em 12/09, para solicitar a troca do cartucho defeituoso.

No entanto, fui atendido pelo senhor Arlen, que se identificou como supervisor, e fui informado de que a loja não realiza a troca do cartucho, orientando-me a entrar em contato diretamente com o 0800 da HP. Ele alegou que, após a saída do produto da loja, não há mais responsabilidade sobre o item, afirmando que a responsabilidade é exclusivamente da fabricante.

Gostaria de destacar que, de acordo com o Código de Defesa do Consumidor, produtos com defeitos ou vícios devem ser trocados ou o valor ressarcido, visto que o defeito compromete o uso adequado do produto. Além disso, o atendimento do senhor Arlen foi extremamente inadequado, sem qualquer intenção de resolver a situação de forma amigável, o que prejudica a imagem da empresa diante do mercado.

Solicito que o caso seja revisado e que medidas adequadas sejam tomadas para solucionar o problema o quanto antes.

Atenciosamente, 
Raquel Souza

latestComments/2/text: I bought an HP 5101 Printer three months ago and loved it until the carriage broke. Because it was under warranty, they asked that I send it back which I did. Took a week for them to receive it. I called three times over the course of the following week asking when the replacement would be shipped and they told me that they had yet to register it as received on their end. Finally a new one was shipped out, received it a week later, so three weeks without a printer. Turns out, they do not give you a new printer, it is a refurbish. Of course, I went to use it and there is a massive problem with how it is printing (basically, it printed fine on plain paper but the color was printing only red on glossy paper which is the whole reason I purchased the printer). I spent 1.5 hours on the phone with them with the support person who maintained the whole time that all of their refurbished printers are tested to factory levels (if all was equal, why not just send me a new printer?) and that I had to send the printer back again to receive another. If the past wait time of three weeks is expected this time around, that will mean six weeks without a printer and interruption to my business. Because of this, I looked at the BBB's review of HP and am stunned that every single office is rated an "F." Be advised that they do not replace a broken printer under warranty with a new printer, that it will be a refurbished one, and expect to have a significant downtime in your work without a printer.

caption:
Back-to-school season usually means new tech ✨💻 When upgrading your old devices make sure you follow these sustainability tips #HPGoBeyond

1. Look for an ecolabel. Ecolabels exist to help consumers identify companies and products that meet standards for environmental responsibility.

2. Transfer and protect your data from your old device. No matter what you do with an existing device, you’ll want to preserve important files and protect your personal information — including passwords. You can either transfer this data to your new device or back up on an external hard drive and then return your old device to factory settings before donating/recycling.

3. Donate your gear to extend your hardware’s life. A lot of devices still have a lot of life left in them when we upgrade. Find a donation program like World Computer Exchange that donates refurbished devices to those who need access to technology.

4. Recycle your tech to keep materials in the loop. If your device is old or damaged beyond repair, recycling is the next best option after donating. Programs like HP Planet Partners [keep harmful substances out of landfills and gives reusable materials like plastic new life in new products](https://bit.ly/3syhACn)
